Definitely agree on the antisemitism.    

I remember when I first read about critical race theory and thought how it can be easily applied to how Jewish people are perceived. Someone might not believe they are being antisemitic because they:    

(a) perceive themselves to be tolerant and would surely reject something so illogical.   
(b) cannot see that their thinking is clouded by the antisemitic tropes that have seeped into ‘normal’ thinking through their being so persistent and pervasive.

bridge_candidates.comment_b:
Well, I typically say the most theological and least targeted-towards-people thing I can say for a given truth. 


Like if I say, "Those who didn't follow Moses are rejected, and where does it leave those that don't follow Jesus, the greater one to come who Moses said to follow?" I am not saying anything about any individual or even any group, only about an action, a choice that a person can make.


But I think that we have to be careful not to turn theological accuracy into hatred. To be theologically accurate while believing Jesus, I believe that following Jesus is right and not following Him is wrong. By that I do not intend anything hateful; I know God's love is for the world, and He wishes all to be saved. (Just, I believe that Jesus is the Gate; I don't see salvation without Him.)



I guess maybe that's the key... Not just for antisemitic but also other types of would be hateful views... If we condemn and glory in that, or hope for or celebrate God's judgment, that is far greater risk of being hateful than an attitude like Paul, who yearned for his brethren to be saved, in Romans 9:1-4 and Romans 10:1.


And I think it goes without saying that judgement on current/modern policies and decisions is not ethnic or hateful.

If you want to be a religious sister, you're mostly limited to the Roman Catholics. They have a lot of options.

There are a couple of very small Episcopal monastic orders. You can find them here: [https://www.episcopalchurch.org/organizations-affiliations/religious-orders-and-christian-communities/listings/](https://www.episcopalchurch.org/organizations-affiliations/religious-orders-and-christian-communities/listings/)

Being a lesbian isn't a major issue for a religious sister, as you'd be required to be celibate anyway. Celibacy is the RCC's required stance for people with same-sex attraction (and there are some voices in the church that are advocating for more inclusion for LGBTQ+ people),but, again, religious sisters are required to be celibate anyway. 

So, before you even start exploring a monastic/religious vocation, you're going to need to join the church that the order is associated with. I will (of course) recommend the Episcopal Church, because we are affirming of LGBTQ people. But that will limit your vocational options.

The sister of a friend from high school is a Catholic nun, and, by all accounts, is quite happy with her choice. I believe she had a two-year novitiate, during which she lived as a sister, but was not yet under vows.
